Reporting to the Head of Legal and Corporate Affairs at British American Tobacco (BAT), Catherine's responsibilities included strategic repositioning of the company - and indeed, the sector - as a major and legitimate contributor to the Australian community and meeting well-documented consumer demand, enhancing the Company's internal and external communications, being BAT's media spokesperson and participating in cross-sector campaigns to promote the interests of the Company and the sector generally.

Key achievements included:

- a lobbying campaign which achieved maintenance of tobacco sector equilibrium by securing an amendment to a proposed Federal Government taxation reform package; 

- securing a significant 'share of voice' and 'place at the negotiating table' for a company facing enormous challenges to its commercial rights from media, politicians, bureaucrats and regulators, some sections of the FMCG sector, a very well-organised anti-tobacco movement and some sections of the community;

- developing and implementing a media strategy which raised the company's profile as a major members of the Australian tobacco industry. This assisted the company in its negotiations with a number of parties, including policy makers and regulators, which gave us a commercial advantage over our competitors;

- developing a revised internal communications strategy, based on the findings of a comprehensive internal communications audit and climate survey; 

- as Merger Communications Manager, developing an effective merger communications strategy; and developing and implementing a media strategy which raised the profile and asserted the legitimacy of BAT and the tobacco sector.
